3. quis] This is probably the dative case, and refers to the terror inspired in Tiridates and his party by the approach of the Scythians. Dillenbr. prefers taking it as the nominative case, and it is not easy to decide which it is; in the loose way of talking Horace may either mean he does not care who is the king of the Scythians, or who is afraid of the king of the Scythians. Either contains meaning enough for the occasion. See Introduction.
